Load all three datasets into one AnnData object by "concatenating" multiple anndata objects.

DATADIR=os.environ["HOME"]+"/public/lab6"
dsets = ["GSM5114461_S6_A11", "GSM5114464_S7_D20", "GSM5114474_M3_E7"]
adatas = {}
for ds in dsets:
    print(ds)
    adatas[ds] = sc.read_10x_mtx(DATADIR, prefix=ds+"_", cache=True)
combined = ad.concat(adatas, label="dataset")
combined.obs_names_make_unique()

sc.pp.filter_cells(combined, min_counts = 1000) # min 1000 counts (> 1000 reads)
sc.pp.filter_cells(combined, min_genes = 200) # min 200 genes (> 200 genes expressed)
sc.pp.filter_genes(combined, min_counts = 15) # min 15 counts (> 15 total count)
sc.pp.filter_genes(combined, min_cells = 5) # min 5 cells (> 5 cells)

# Determine the percent of counts in each cell that are from mitochondrial genes.
combined.var['highPercent'] = combined.var_names.str.startswith('MT')
sc.pp.calculate_qc_metrics(combined, qc_vars = ['highPercent'], percent_top = None, log1p = False, inplace = True)

# Visualize violin and scatter plots of QC metrics including the percent mitochondria per cell, the count number per cell, and the number of genes per cell.
sc.pl.violin(combined, ['pct_counts_highPercent', 'total_counts', 'n_genes_by_counts'], jitter = 0.4, multi_panel = True)
sc.pl.scatter(combined, x = 'total_counts', y = 'pct_counts_highPercent')
sc.pl.scatter(combined, x = 'total_counts', y = 'n_genes_by_counts')
sc.pl.scatter(combined, x = 'n_genes_by_counts', y = 'pct_counts_highPercent')
In [13]:
# Filter cells with a high percentage of counts from mitochondrial genes. The paper we got the data from suggested using 25% as a threshold.
adata_filt = combined[(combined.obs.pct_counts_highPercent < 25) & (combined.obs.total_counts < 70000), :] # Also filter out counts that are too high, use 75000 as threshold
In [14]:
# Normalizing Counts
sc.pp.normalize_per_cell(combined, counts_per_cell_after=1e4) # normalize to 10,000 reads/cell
sc.pp.log1p(combined) # log transform
